'''Heart of the Earth School''' was a Native American survival school located in [[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]. Established in 1972, the school served students in kindergarten through twelfth grade until its closure in 2008.

==History==
Heart of the Earth Survival School was established in January 1972<ref>{{cite news |title=Heart of Indian school beats strongly |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=1992-03-09 |quote=There were no desks, pencils or paper when the school for American Indians opened with two children in January of that year... }}</ref> by the [[American Indian Movement]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Jenna |last=Ross |title=Minneapolis charter school director allegedly embezzled $1.38 million |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/46627937.html |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=2009-06-01 |accessdate=2009-12-07 }}</ref> Instrumental in the creation of Heart of the Earth was Title IV of the Indian Education Act, adopted by Congress on June 23, 1972.<ref name="glogower">{{cite web |first=Ari |last=Glogower |title=The Indian Education Act of 1972 |url=http://www.olemiss.edu/programs/mtc/Media/Writings/docs/.../Ari.pdf |accessdate=2009-11-15 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> This act allowed Indians to have control over educating their people; a different policy than the US government had previously adopted with the [[Native American boarding schools|boarding schools]] that dominated Indian education throughout the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name="glogower" /> 

In 1999, Heart of the Earth/Oh Day Aki became a charter school.<ref>{{cite news |title=School revival is at the heart of test success |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=1999-05-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Editorial: Indian school closure holds lessons |url=http://www.startribune.com/opinion/editorials/26932639.html |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=2008-08-13 |accessdate=2009-12-07 }}</ref> Minneapolis Public Schools ended the district's sponsorship of the school in August 2008 after an audit revealed more than $160,000 in financial discrepancies.<ref>{{cite news |first=Patrice |last=Relerford |title=Minneapolis cuts ties to Heart of the Earth charter school |url=http://www.startribune.com/local/26893059.html |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=2008-08-12 |accessdate=2009-12-07 }}</ref>

==Campus==
The school's location on 4th Street Southeast was located in the [[Dinkytown]] district of the [[Marcy-Holmes, Minneapolis|Marcy-Holmes]] neighborhood of Minneapolis.

==Curriculum==
A <U+201C>survival school<U+201D> serves as an alternative to public and [[Bureau of Indian Affairs]] schools offered most commonly to Indian communities on reservations. Survival schools provide language instruction in native languages like [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]] and [[Lakota language|Lakota]]. The courses, even the basics, are centered on Indian culture.<ref name="fardelmann">{{cite news |first=Charlotte |last=Fardelmann |title=Survival Schools Rescue Indian Students, Culture |work=Christian Science Monitor |date=1983-03-17 |accessdate=2009-10-20 }}</ref> Part of Heart of the Earth<U+2019>s original purpose was to teach Indian children living in cities about disappearing life skills like "hunting, fishing, maple syrup gathering and wild rice harvesting", and helping Indian students identify to their culture.<ref name="norrell">{{cite web |first=Brenda |last=Norrell |title=Gentle Rage: Clyde Bellecourt remembers the birth of the American Indian Movement |url=http://narcosphere.narconews.com/notebook/brenda-norrell/2008/08/gentle-rage-clyde-bellecourt-remembers-birth-american-indian-movemen |accessdate=2009-10-26 }}</ref>  Initially, the school provided practical training for Indian students who would not pursue higher education.<ref name="fardelmann" /> Later, as a charter school, Oh Day Aki provided a unique opportunity for Indian students to explore their cultures in a school setting while simultaneously preparing for higher education and self-sufficiency.<ref name="schoolchange">{{cite web |title=Oh Day Aki (Heart of the Earth) Charter School |url=http://www.centerforschoolchange.org/index.php?option=com_comprofiler&task=userProfile&user=179 |publisher=Center for School Change |accessdate=2009-10-26 }}</ref>

==Extracurricular activities==
Oh Day Aki Charter School's athletic teams, known as the Eagles,<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Nelson |title=American Indian charter school faces closure |url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2008/08/08/charter_school_close/ |publisher=Minnesota Public Radio |date=2008-08-08 |accessdate=2009-12-07 }}</ref> competed in the [[Minnesota State High School League]], Class A, Section 4. The school fielded teams in baseball, basketball,<ref>{{cite news |title=After 16 years, basketball arrives at Heart of the Earth |work=Minneapolis Star-Tribune |date=1988-01-21 |quote=Until this season the Heart of the Earth, an all-American Indian school in southeast Minneapolis with an enrollment of 75, didn't field athletic teams. }}</ref> cross country, softball, track, and volleyball.

